newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soy products close higher on soybean rally.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soy products close higher on soybean rally.

text.p: CBOT soy product futures closed sharply higher on a rally in soybeans tied to fund buying, bull spreading and a surge to one month highs in the neighboring wheat pit, traders said.
Recent active export sales of U.S. soybeans and soy products also nudged some shorts out of the market.
"In the complex, people wanted to be long before the export sales report tomorrow," said Mark Cermak of O'Connor and Co.
At 0730 CST Friday, USDA will release its updated weekly export sales report.
Trade sources said the net export sales tally for soyoil were expected at 50,000 to 65,000 tonnnes and soymeal at 150,000 to 200,000 tonnes.
After the close, U.S. exporters reported 20,000 tonnes of U.S. soyoil sold to China for quick shipment.
Soyoil closed 0.12 to 0.23 cent higher, with December up 0.21 at 23.37 cents a lb. Soymeal settled $1.70 to $3.60 higher, with December up $3.60 at $240.00 per ton.
Soyoil futures volume was estimated at 15,000 contracts, below the 17,560 traded Tuesday, according to CBOT. Soymeal volume was estimated at 25,000 contracts, up from 23,478 traded Tuesday.
